snippet.textDisplay: Is this a joke? Does Coke Studio know the rich history of Dhadi Jatha, and choose to ignore it, or are they just that ignorant? Do a quick Wikipedia search and find out for yourself. Dhadi Jatha is unique to the Punjab region. It gained popularity when Guru Hargobind, a Sikh Guru for those of you who refuse to educate yourself on the fifth largest religion in the world, promoted the art and transformed it from a method to sing common songs about folk heroes and beautiful woman to a platform that spread the message of Sikhi. Thanks to Guru Hargobind, Dhadi Jatha was elevated from street music to a disciplined art form that was performed in His court, and the topics changed from worldly topics to stories about Sikh warriors/wars and Gurbani. Coke Studio India has raped this vanishing art by having idiots sing "Namaste" in between lines about the importance of being true to God. You don't see Lil Wayne sampling Gospel music about Jesus in his songs, and Drake doesn't use Bible verses in between his songs. But we all let Coke Studio India butcher our culture for the sake of...what? What is the purpose of this song? It isn't a preservation of Punjabi Culture. This is killing our culture. Wake up, people. I'm not going to say this is a typical move done by India to make Punjabi's forget their own unique identity, because then people will think I'm being "crazy" with my "conspiracies." But notice how Punjabi music is now popular in Bollywood, but only as a fad. Ever heard of the term "Cultural Appropriation"? Here is exhibit A, right in front of you. Taking Dhadi Jatha, a form of music known for its strong ties to Sikhi and known to be preserved through the efforts of our Gurus, and throwing it in the gutter with some fool making weird "ting-a-ling" noises and Jazz-club-esque backup singers. Stop doing this to my ancestor's culture, Coke Studio India. You're not preserving any region's culture. Rather, you're imposing your Nationalistic views on cultures and trying to colonize the various groups that had the awful misfortune of falling within the geographical region know as "Hindustan."
